            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 9,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1372865982,
            "creation_date": 1372865982,
            "body": "<p>String literals in Java source are <em>interned<\/em>, meaning that all literals with the same text will resolve to the same instance.  <\/p>\n\n<p>In other words, <code>\"A\" == \"A\"<\/code> will be true.<\/p>\n\n<p>Creating a new <code>String<\/code> instance will bypass that; <code>\"A\" == new String(\"A\")<\/code> will not be true.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 17452311,
            "question_id": 17452278
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b64ecf035c26728e5e3635b940d2cd38?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 422964,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 802050,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/802050/m-sach",
                "reputation": 34570,
                "display_name": "M Sach",
                "accept_rate": 89
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 4,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1372866656,
            "creation_date": 1372866150,
            "body": "<pre><code>String tmp1 = \"someString\"; \nString tmp2 = new String(\"someString\");\nString tmp3 = \"someString\"; \n\n if(tmp1 == tmp2)/* will return false as both are different objects\n                     stored at differnt location in heap */\n\n if(tmp1.equals(tmp2))/* will return true as it will compare the values \n                        not object reference */\n\n if(tmp1 == tmp3)/* will return true. see string literals and they are interned. \n                  brief about them is they  are stored in pool in  permgen  till \n                  java 6.They are stored as part of heap only in java 7\n                  Every time u create string literal with same value , \n                  it will refer from same location in pool instead of creating \n                  object each time */\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 17452379,
            "question_id": 17452278,
            "last_edit_date": 1372866656
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cf9ec57f64280ffe34ddd221d5c5151f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 61473,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 183203,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/183203/antlersoft",
                "reputation": 14771,
                "display_name": "antlersoft",
                "accept_rate": 75
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1372866321,
            "creation_date": 1372866321,
            "body": "<p>String in Java source are stored in a constants table in the .class file.  When a class file is loaded, all the strings in the constants table are interned; unique strings are converted to object instances.  References to them refer to the interned instance, so additional references don't generate additional objects. <\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 17452445,
            "question_id": 17452278
        }
